It was a quarter past six when we left BakerStreet, and it still wanted tenminutes to the hour when we found ourselves in Serpentine Avenue. It was alreadydusk, and the lamps were just being lighted aswe paced up anddown in front ofBriony Lodge, waiting for the coming of its occupant. The housewas just such as I had picturedit from Sherlock Holmes' succinct description,but the localityappeared to beless private than I expected. Onthe contrary, for a small street in a quiet neighbourhood, it was remarkably animated. There was a group of shabbily dressed men smoking and laughing in a corner, a scissors-grinder with hiswheel, two guardsmen who were flirting with a nurse-girl, and several well-dressed young men whowere lounging up and down withcigars in theirmouths.

